        <div class="article_promo_inner clearfix"> <img class="author" src="/images/photos/mike.jpg" alt="" width="90" height="117" />
          <div class="article_promo_body">
            <p>Read Michael Jacobson's column on the <i>Huffington Post</i></p>
             <h2><a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-f-jacobson/whole-grain-foods_b_1269613.html" target="_blank">Are Your 'Whole Grains' Really Whole? Maybe. Maybe Not. </a>&raquo;</h2>
            <p>Kellogg's probably wouldn't sell a lot of Eggo waffles of any variety if their labels proclaimed that the waffles were "made with water" and "mostly white flour." Yet water and white flour are the top two ingredients in Eggo Nutrigrain Whole Wheat Waffles, whose labels tout their "whole grain" and "whole wheat" content. </p>
